               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470816-1919-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1919-18470816 t18470816-1919-offence-1 t18470816-1919-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470816-1919-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1919-18470816 t18470816-1919-offence-2 t18470816-1919-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>1919. <persName id="def1-1919-18470816" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18470816" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18470816" type="surname" value="WAKEFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1919-18470816" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">GEORGE WAKEFIELD</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18470816-1919-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1919-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1919-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> staling 3 bushels of beans, value 16<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; and 4 sacks 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18470816-name-1029" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1029" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1029" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1029" type="given" value="WALTER"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470816-1919-offence-1 t18470816-name-1029"></join>Walter Powell</persName>, his master: and </rs>
                  <persName id="def2-1919-18470816" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1919-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1919-18470816" type="surname" value="GOBBY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1919-18470816" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">CHARLES GOBBY</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18470816-1919-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1919-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1919-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp> for feloniously receiving the same, well-knowing them to have been stolen.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1031" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1031" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1031" type="surname" value="LOADES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1031" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY LOADES.</persName>
                  </hi> I am in the employ of Mr. Walter Powell—I know the prisoner Wakefield—he was in Mr. Powell's employ. On the 1st of July he was ordered to take three sacks of oats and some straw to Mr. Fordham—I helped him load—he told me to take a sack of oats into Gobby's—I took it—I hallooed out, no one answered, and I left it on the stairs—I saw Wake-field again that night—he owed me a shilling, and I asked him if he could pay me, and he gave me 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—the sack of oats came from my master's loft, where the other sacks came from.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184708160184"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What did you get the 3<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know, unless he meant to lend it me—we have been in the habit of lending and borrowing—I am quite innocent—I did not know whether I was doing right or wrong—when I got the extra 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>., I did not ask what it was for—people do not often give me 2<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for nothing—I did not know whether he meant to lend it me—we do lend and borrow, without asking each other for it—I left the sack with a little girl, and said, "Here is a sack of oats for Mr. Gobby"—I have known Gobby to be a customer of my master's—I have not lent him any sacks—I do not know whether he has had sacks of my master—when he has bought things, he has brought his own sack—I never knew sacks of my master's to go there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1032" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1032" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1032" type="surname" value="OAKFORD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1032" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY OAKFORD.</persName>
                  </hi> I live in Hatton-garden. On the 1st of July, between three and four o'clock, I saw a sack taken to Gobby's premises by Wakefield—it appeared to be full—I could not see what was in it—it was a new sack, similar to this one, and marked in red letters, "W. Powell."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1033" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1033" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1033" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1033" type="given" value="WALTER"></interp>WALTER POWELL.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a corn-dealer, and live in Leather-lane—Gobby has bought things at my place—the last oats he bought of me, was on the 10th of March—in consequence of information I went to his house with a constable—when he came home, I asked him if he had any empty sacks of mine—he denied it strongly—I said, "I think you have"—I went into his stable, and he <hi rend="italic">chucked</hi> a sack off a rail—I said that was not mine—he then <hi rend="italic">chucked</hi> down two sacks, which were mine—he said he did not know how he came by them, he used them for chaff—I looked into one, and I said, "This does not look like chaff; here are oats in this"—I then asked if he had any more sacks—he said, "No, only those two empty sacks"—I said I was quite certain he had got sacks up stairs—he said he had no place up stairs, and he was quite sure he had no sacks at all up stairs—I then asked him if he would allow me and the officer to go up—he said it was no use going, there were no sacks there—we went up, and there was a sack in the pas<lb></lb>sage—it could not be seen from the bottom—it contained about a bushel and a half oats—I looked at them, and said, "These are some of my oats"—Gobby said, "Yes, I had them of George"—we asked him to let us go up higher—he said he had nothing more—we went up, and found a sack with a bushel and a half of beans—he said, "I did not have them of your man; I took your sack to fetch them in"—I opened the sack, and I said, "These are my beans"—he said, "Yes, I had them of George," or "the man"—I said, "What do you mean by allowing me to be robbed?"—he said he hoped I would forgive him, that he had seven or nine children, and he said, "George told me he worked at a vessel, and he had got these overplus"—he said he gave the man a sovereign for the oats and beans, <hi rend="italic">through</hi> his spending a shilling, and he borrowed part of the money at the public-house—I gave 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 0<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. a quarter for the beans, on the 9th of Jan., but as they were damaged, I should have taken perhaps 38<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for them—they heated in the sacks, and were damaged a little.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> In fact they were damaged? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They were good beans when I bought them—they had heated, and there were a few sacks a little damaged—those I found at Gobby's were so damaged, that I could not send them to customers as sweet beans—there were plenty of them good—they were worth 4<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. a bushel—I should be sure to get that for them if I had them at home—I might not have said at the Police-office that he begged I would forgive him—I will not swear that I said anything about his wife and children.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184708160185"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1034" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1034" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1034" type="surname" value="GUNN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1034" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN GUNN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman G</hi> 224.) I went with the prosecutor to Gobby's—he came home with his van—the prosecutor asked him if he had any of his sacks on his premises—he hesitated, and said he did not know, or something to that effect—the gates of the stable were wide open, and we walked in—Gobby took two sacks off he place, and said, "I believe I have a sack or two of yours here"—the first he took, Mr. Powell said, "This is not mine"—he took down two more, and Mr. Powell said, "These are mine; how did you come by them?"—he said, "I do not know, they have been here some time"—Mr. Powell said, "Have you got any up stairs?"—he said, "Up stairs I have got no place for sacks"—Mr. Powell said, "I am informed you have; will you allow, me to look?"—he said, "I have no place up stairs"—I then said, "I am a constable; if you have no sacks, you can have no objection to our going up"—he said, "I have only got my room up stairs," and he looked round the stable, and said, "Here is all the place I have got for food for my horse"—at last he said, "We will all go up stairs"—there is a door from the stable to the bottom of the stair-case, and as soon as that was opened, on the first step, I tumbled against a sack—I showed it to Mr. Powell—he said, "This is one of my sacks; will you allow me to look at the corn?"—Gobby said, "Yes"—Mr. Powell put his hand in, and said, "This is very much like my corn"—Gobby said, "I know it is, I bought it of your George"—we went up stairs, and in the bedroom found two sacks—one con<lb></lb>tained whole beans, and one split beans—Mr. Powell put his hand in the latter, and said, "These are my beans"—Gobby said, "Yes, I know they are; I bought them of your George the same time that 1 bought the oats"—Mr. Powell said, "How could you rob me in that manner?"—he said, "George told me there was an over plus of the vessel, and I paid him a sovereign, and he spent a shilling"—he talked about his looking over it, but I will not sat what—my attention was directed to the beans.</p>
               <p>(Gobby received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">WAKEFIELD</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
